        How the First Home Guarantee Affects Property Sales in Brisbane: A Seller's Perspective
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The First Home Guarantee scheme can expand your buyer pool, but it also changes how some offers are structured and financed. Here is what Brisbane sellers need to understand.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most conversation about the First Home Guarantee focuses on buyers: how it works, who qualifies, and how to apply. But the scheme also has practical implications for sellers, particularly around offer evaluation, finance conditions, and settlement timelines. If your property falls within the scheme's price caps and your agent thinks first home buyers are likely to be in the buyer pool, understanding how the scheme works from the seller's side is worth your time.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the First Home Guarantee actually does</h2>
      <p>The First Home Guarantee (previously called the First Home Loan Deposit Scheme) is a federal government program administered through Housing Australia. It allows eligible first home buyers to purchase a property with a 5% deposit without paying lenders mortgage insurance. The government acts as guarantor for the remaining portion of the 20% deposit threshold, effectively covering the LMI shortfall that would otherwise apply to a high-LVR loan.</p>

      <p>The scheme does not provide the buyer with cash. It does not cover the deposit itself. What it does is remove the LMI cost, which for a buyer borrowing at 95% of a property's value can represent several thousand to tens of thousands of dollars. For buyers who have saved a 5% deposit but do not have the additional funds for LMI, the scheme can be the difference between being able to transact or not.</p>

      <p>From 1 October 2025 the scheme was materially expanded. The cap on the number of places has been removed (previously 35,000 per year), income caps have been removed, and price caps have been raised. Buyers no longer compete for a limited allocation. Buyers apply through one of the participating lenders and have the guarantee confirmed as part of the loan application. This process has its own timeline, separate from standard mortgage approval.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Price caps and which Brisbane properties qualify</h2>
      <p>The scheme applies only to properties priced at or below the relevant cap for the area. From 1 October 2025 the Brisbane price cap is $1,000,000, covering both Brisbane capital city and regional Queensland. Earlier iterations of the scheme used caps as low as $500,000 to $700,000 in Brisbane, but those are no longer current.</p>

      <p>At the current $1,000,000 cap, the scheme is relevant to a much wider band of inner-east stock than it was before. Entry-level houses in Murarrie, Cannon Hill, Seven Hills, Coorparoo and Carina often fall inside the cap. Most units and townhouses across Camp Hill, Morningside, Hawthorne, Bulimba, and Norman Park sit inside the cap. Prestige houses in Balmoral, Hawthorne and Bulimba above $1 million still fall outside it, but that group is smaller than it was under older caps.</p>

      <p>Before assuming the scheme is or is not relevant to your sale, ask your agent what proportion of inquiries in your suburb and price range are likely to be first home buyers using the guarantee. For properties at or below the cap, the scheme materially widens the buyer pool.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What it means when a buyer uses the scheme</h2>
      <p>If you receive an offer from a buyer who is using the First Home Guarantee, there are a few things worth understanding.</p>

      <p>First, these buyers typically have a 5% deposit, not the 10% or 20% that established buyers in your market may bring. A lower deposit does not in itself make a buyer unreliable, but it does mean there is less buffer in the event of any issue between exchange and settlement. Buyers with smaller deposits have less capacity to absorb unexpected costs or to renegotiate through a formal channel if complications arise.</p>

      <p>Second, the finance approval process for a guaranteed loan can involve additional steps compared with a standard mortgage. The lender needs to confirm the guarantee has been allocated and is valid for the specific property. This can add time to the approval process, which means a subject-to-finance condition in the contract may need a longer finance period than you might otherwise expect. Your agent should discuss this with you before the finance clause deadline is agreed.</p>

      <p>Third, the lender's own assessment of the property's value is particularly important when the buyer is borrowing at 95%. If the bank's valuation comes in below the purchase price, the buyer's borrowing capacity is constrained in a way that a buyer with a larger deposit would be better placed to absorb. Valuations coming in below contract price are not unique to this buyer type, but the margin for adjustment is narrower.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions to ask your agent before accepting an offer</h2>
      <p>If your agent presents you with an offer from a buyer using the First Home Guarantee or a similar low-deposit scheme, the most useful questions to ask are straightforward. Has the buyer been pre-approved by a participating lender, and has the guarantee been confirmed rather than just applied for? What is the proposed finance clause period, and is it long enough to allow for the additional lender steps involved? Has the buyer's broker or bank indicated any concerns about the property type or price point that could affect valuation?</p>

      <p>A good agent will already have had most of these conversations with the buyer's broker before presenting the offer. The answers give you a clearer read on the settlement risk and help you compare the offer accurately against others you might receive.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the scheme shapes the buyer pool for inner east Brisbane</h2>
      <p>The First Home Guarantee, alongside the Queensland First Home Owner Grant and other state and federal assistance measures, has kept a segment of first home buyers active in the market through periods of rising prices. For properties that fall within the price caps, this is a genuine source of buyer demand that would not otherwise exist at the same depth.</p>

      <p>In practical terms, at the current $1,000,000 Brisbane cap, this matters for a broader band of stock than the old scheme reached. A two-bedroom unit in Morningside, a townhouse in Camp Hill, an entry-level house in Murarrie or Cannon Hill, or a smaller property in Seven Hills or Carina are all potentially in-cap. Buyers using the guarantee on these properties lean on the state first home concession as well, which compounds the upfront saving.</p>

      <p>For prestige houses above $1,000,000, typically in Hawthorne, Bulimba, Balmoral, and the premium pockets of Norman Park and Camp Hill, the scheme does not apply. The buyer pool for those properties is made up of upsizers, owner-occupiers with existing equity, and investors, none of whom are using the First Home Guarantee. Understanding which buyer types are realistic for your property is the starting point for any sale strategy discussion with your agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The broader picture</h2>
      <p>Government housing assistance schemes change regularly. The First Home Guarantee has been updated, expanded, and rebranded multiple times since it was introduced in 2020. The specific rules, caps, and lender lists that apply at the time you sell may differ from what is described here. Your agent should be across the current version of the scheme and how it affects buyer eligibility for your property type and price range.</p>

      <p>As a seller, the most useful frame for evaluating any buyer is the same regardless of how they are financing: how solid is the finance approval, what are the conditions in the contract, and what is the realistic risk of the sale not proceeding? The First Home Guarantee changes the deposit structure but does not change the fundamental questions you need to answer before accepting an offer.</p>

